name: First Kinematic Equation
description: Relates final velocity, initial velocity, acceleration, and time.
history: This equation originates from classical mechanics, primarily developed during the 17th century by scientists such as Galileo Galilei and Isaac Newton. It forms part of the foundational equations of motion for objects under constant acceleration.

variables.name: Final velocity
variables.description: The velocity of the object at time t.

variables.name: Initial velocity
variables.description: The velocity of the object at the start of observation.

variables.name: Acceleration
variables.description: The rate of change of velocity.

variables.name: Time
variables.description: The time elapsed during motion.

name: Second Kinematic Equation
description: Relates displacement, initial velocity, acceleration, and time.
history: Derived as part of Newtonian mechanics, this equation provides insight into an object's displacement under constant acceleration over time.

variables.name: Displacement
variables.description: The total change in position of the object.

variables.name: Initial velocity
variables.description: The velocity of the object at the start of observation.

variables.name: Acceleration
variables.description: The rate of change of velocity.

variables.name: Time
variables.description: The time elapsed during motion.

name: Third Kinematic Equation
description: Relates final velocity, initial velocity, acceleration, and displacement.
history: This equation is part of the kinematic equations developed during the early study of motion in classical physics. It is especially useful in solving problems without time as a variable.

variables.name: Final velocity
variables.description: The velocity of the object at the end of observation.

variables.name: Initial velocity
variables.description: The velocity of the object at the start of observation.

variables.name: Acceleration
variables.description: The rate of change of velocity.

variables.name: Displacement
variables.description: The total change in position of the object.

name: Fourth Kinematic Equation
description: Relates displacement, average velocity, and time.
history: This equation simplifies displacement calculations by relating the average velocity during motion to the time elapsed, developed alongside Newtonian mechanics.

variables.name: Displacement
variables.description: The total change in position of the object.

variables.name: Initial velocity
variables.description: The velocity of the object at the start of observation.

variables.name: Final velocity
variables.description: The velocity of the object at the end of observation.

variables.name: Time
variables.description: The time elapsed during motion.

name: Ideal Gas Law
description: Relates pressure, volume, number of moles, and temperature of an ideal gas.
history: The Ideal Gas Law is a combination of Boyle's, Charles', and Avogadro's laws. Benoît Paul Émile Clapeyron formulated this law in its modern form in 1834, bridging observations into a single comprehensive relationship.

variables.name: Pressure
variables.description: The force exerted by the gas per unit area.

variables.name: Volume
variables.description: The space occupied by the gas.

variables.name: Number of moles
variables.description: The amount of gas in moles.

variables.name: Gas constant
variables.description: A constant relating energy scale to temperature for an ideal gas.

variables.name: Temperature
variables.description: The absolute temperature of the gas.

name: Schwarzschild Radius
description: Defines the radius of the event horizon for a non-rotating black hole.
history: The Schwarzschild radius was derived by Karl Schwarzschild in 1916, shortly after Albert Einstein presented his theory of general relativity. It describes the critical radius where the escape velocity equals the speed of light, marking the boundary of a black hole.

variables.name: Schwarzschild radius
variables.description: The radius of the event horizon of the black hole.

variables.name: Gravitational constant
variables.description: The universal constant of gravitation.

variables.name: Mass
variables.description: The mass of the black hole.

variables.name: Speed of light
variables.description: The speed of light in a vacuum.

name: Vis-Viva Equation
description: Describes the orbital velocity of a body at a specific distance from the primary focus.
history: The vis-viva equation was formulated during the 18th century by astronomers and mathematicians studying orbital mechanics, notably Johann Bernoulli and later formalized in the context of celestial motion.

variables.name: Orbital velocity
variables.description: The speed of the orbiting body at a given point in orbit.

variables.name: Gravitational constant
variables.description: The universal constant of gravitation.

variables.name: Mass of the primary body
variables.description: The mass of the central body being orbited.

variables.name: Orbital radius
variables.description: The distance of the orbiting body from the central body.

variables.name: Semi-major axis
variables.description: The semi-major axis of the elliptical orbit.

name: Einstein's Mass-Energy Equivalence
description: Relates mass and energy through the speed of light in a vacuum.
history: This famous equation was introduced by Albert Einstein in his 1905 paper on special relativity. It demonstrates that mass and energy are interchangeable, providing a profound insight into the fundamental nature of matter and energy.

variables.name: Energy
variables.description: The total energy equivalent to the object's mass.

variables.name: Mass
variables.description: The mass of the object.

variables.name: Speed of light
variables.description: The constant speed of light in a vacuum.

name: Hardy-Weinberg Equilibrium
description: Predicts genetic variation in a population at equilibrium.
history: Developed independently by G.H. Hardy and Wilhelm Weinberg in 1908, this equation describes the genetic structure of populations not influenced by evolution, such as selection or mutation.

variables.name: Frequency of dominant homozygotes
variables.description: The proportion of individuals with two dominant alleles.

variables.name: Frequency of heterozygotes
variables.description: The proportion of individuals with one dominant and one recessive allele.

variables.name: Frequency of recessive homozygotes
variables.description: The proportion of individuals with two recessive alleles.

name: Black-Scholes Formula for Call Option Price
description: Calculates the theoretical price of a European call option.
history: The Black-Scholes model was introduced in 1973 by Fischer Black, Myron Scholes, and Robert Merton. It provided a revolutionary framework for pricing financial options.

variables.name: Call option price
variables.description: The theoretical price of the European call option.

variables.name: Spot price of the asset
variables.description: The current market price of the underlying asset.

variables.name: Strike price
variables.description: The price at which the option holder can buy the asset.

variables.name: Risk-free interest rate
variables.description: The annualized rate of return on a risk-free investment.

variables.name: Time to maturity
variables.description: The time until the option expires.

variables.name: Cumulative normal distribution function
variables.description: Represents the probability that a variable is below d_1 or d_2.

name: Ohm's Law
description: Relates voltage, current, and resistance in an electrical circuit.
history: Ohm's Law was formulated by German physicist Georg Simon Ohm in 1827. It describes the linear relationship between voltage, current, and resistance in conductive materials.

variables.name: Voltage
variables.description: The potential difference across the circuit.

variables.name: Current
variables.description: The flow of electric charge.

variables.name: Resistance
variables.description: The opposition to current flow in the circuit.

name: Planck's Law
description: Describes the spectral radiance of electromagnetic radiation as a function of wavelength for a black body in thermal equilibrium.
history: Max Planck introduced this law in 1900 as part of his quantum theory, which explained black body radiation and led to the development of quantum mechanics.

variables.name: Spectral radiance
variables.description: The emitted power per unit area per unit solid angle per unit wavelength.

variables.name: Planck's constant
variables.description: A fundamental constant in quantum mechanics.

variables.name: Speed of light
variables.description: The speed of light in a vacuum.

variables.name: Wavelength
variables.description: The distance between successive peaks of the electromagnetic wave.

variables.name: Boltzmann constant
variables.description: Relates the average kinetic energy of particles to temperature.

variables.name: Temperature
variables.description: The absolute temperature of the black body.

name: Pythagorean Theorem
description: Relates the sides of a right triangle.
history: The Pythagorean theorem, attributed to the ancient Greek mathematician Pythagoras, has been known since antiquity. It states that the square of the hypotenuse is equal to the sum of the squares of the other two sides.

variables.name: Side A
variables.description: One of the shorter sides of the right triangle.

variables.name: Side B
variables.description: The other shorter side of the right triangle.

variables.name: Hypotenuse
variables.description: The longest side of the right triangle, opposite the right angle.

name: Coulomb's Law
description: Describes the electrostatic force between two charged objects.
history: Coulomb's law was formulated by Charles-Augustin de Coulomb in 1785. It quantifies the magnitude of the electrostatic force between two charges.

variables.name: Electrostatic force
variables.description: The force between the two charged objects.

variables.name: Coulomb's constant
variables.description: A proportionality constant in electrostatics.

variables.name: Charge 1
variables.description: The magnitude of the first charge.

variables.name: Charge 2
variables.description: The magnitude of the second charge.

variables.name: Distance
variables.description: The separation between the charges.

name: Bernoulli's Equation
description: Describes the conservation of energy in fluid dynamics.
history: Bernoulli's equation was introduced by Daniel Bernoulli in 1738. It explains the relationship between pressure, velocity, and height in a fluid flow.

variables.name: Pressure
variables.description: The pressure within the fluid.

variables.name: Density
variables.description: The density of the fluid.

variables.name: Velocity
variables.description: The velocity of the fluid at a point.

variables.name: Gravitational acceleration
variables.description: The acceleration due to gravity.

variables.name: Height
variables.description: The height above a reference point.

name: Wave Equation
description: Describes the propagation of waves, including electromagnetic waves, through a medium.
history: The wave equation was developed in the 18th century, attributed to Jean le Rond d'Alembert, Leonhard Euler, and Daniel Bernoulli. It is fundamental to understanding wave behavior, including light and sound.

variables.name: Wave function
variables.description: Represents the displacement of the wave at a given point and time.

variables.name: Time
variables.description: The time variable.

variables.name: Wave speed
variables.description: The speed at which the wave propagates.

variables.name: Laplacian
variables.description: The spatial part of the wave equation.

name: Maxwell's Equations (Faraday's Law)
description: Describes how a changing magnetic field creates an electric field.
history: Faraday's Law is part of Maxwell's equations, formulated by James Clerk Maxwell in the 1860s. It unifies electricity and magnetism, explaining the fundamental relationship between changing magnetic and electric fields.

variables.name: Electric field
variables.description: The electric field vector.

variables.name: Magnetic field
variables.description: The magnetic field vector.

variables.name: Time
variables.description: The time variable.

name: Fourier Transform
description: Transforms a signal from the time domain to the frequency domain.
history: The Fourier Transform is named after Joseph Fourier, who introduced the Fourier series in 1822. It became a cornerstone in signal processing and the analysis of electromagnetic waves.

variables.name: Frequency domain function
variables.description: The representation of the signal in the frequency domain.

variables.name: Time domain function
variables.description: The original signal as a function of time.

variables.name: Angular frequency
variables.description: The angular frequency in radians per second.

variables.name: Time
variables.description: The time variable.

variables.name: Complex exponential
variables.description: The kernel of the Fourier transform.

name: Schrödinger Equation
description: Describes how the quantum state of a physical system changes with time.
latex_equation: i\hbar \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\Psi(\mathbf{r}, t) = -\frac{\hbar^2}{2m}\nabla^2\Psi(\mathbf{r}, t) + V(\mathbf{r}, t)\Psi(\mathbf{r}, t)
history: The Schrödinger equation was formulated by Austrian physicist Erwin Schrödinger in 1926. It is a cornerstone of quantum mechanics, describing the evolution of a quantum state over time.

variables.name: Wavefunction
variables.description: Represents the quantum state of the system.

variables.name: Reduced Planck's constant
variables.description: A fundamental constant in quantum mechanics.

variables.name: Time
variables.description: The time variable.

variables.name: Mass
variables.description: The mass of the particle.

variables.name: Laplacian
variables.description: Represents the spatial second derivative.

variables.name: Potential energy
variables.description: The potential energy function of the system.

variables.name: Position
variables.description: The position vector in space.
